## **1. What Are Side Effects in React?**

A **side effect** is anything that happens **outside** React’s rendering process.

Examples:

• Fetching data from an API
• Reading from local storage
• Logging to the console
• Subscribing to events

### **Why React Cares**

React rendering must be **pure**:

```js
UI = f(state)
```

If side effects run during rendering, React can:

• Re-run them multiple times
• Cause infinite loops
• Produce unpredictable behavior

➡️ Side effects must be isolated.

---

## **2. Introducing `useEffect`**

`useEffect` is React’s way to **safely run side effects**.

### **Basic Syntax**

```js
useEffect(() => {
  // side effect logic
}, []);
```

This effect runs **once** when the component mounts.

---

### **The Dependency Array Mental Model**

| Dependency Array | Behavior                  |
| ---------------- | ------------------------- |
| omitted          | Runs on every render      |
| `[]`             | Runs once (on mount)      |
| `[value]`        | Runs when `value` changes |

---

### **Common Beginner Mistake**

❌ This causes an infinite loop:

```js
useEffect(() => {
  setCount(count + 1);
});
```

Why?
• Effect runs
• State updates
• Component re-renders
• Effect runs again

